1. PP grammar bug: The RegexpParser applies NP rule first, consuming <DT>?<JJ>*<NN.*>+
   tokens before the PP rule can match. Result: zero prepositional phrases extracted.
   Fix: change PP rule to {<IN><NP>} to reference the already-chunked NP, or restructure
   the grammar as a cascaded chunker.

2. SHORT mode is on (SHORT=True, SHORT_LIMIT=100). This limits all three exercises to
   100 sentences/paragraphs, producing entity counts and NP counts well below the
   expected assessment ranges. Run with SHORT=False for full results.

3. NLTK ne_chunk false positive rate is extremely high on Joyce's prose. Words like
   "Gelid," "Prr," "Snotgreen," "Ineluctable," "Scratch," "Mouth," "Curious," "Seem,"
   "Afraid," etc. are all misclassified as GPE. This makes the NER comparison between
   Calypso and Proteus unreliable -- the hypothesis (Calypso entity-dense, Proteus
   entity-sparse) appears reversed, but the signal is buried in noise. Consider adding
   a spaCy NER comparison as suggested in the Diving Deeper section.

4. The entity co-occurrence matrix is very sparse: all pair counts are 1. This may be
   partly due to SHORT mode limiting paragraphs, and partly due to the false NER labels
   fragmenting real entity mentions. With better NER and full text, the co-occurrence
   structure should be richer.

5. NP extraction includes noise artifacts: "' t" (from contractions), "prr" (cat sound),
   "stiffly round" (adverb+adjective misparsed as NP). Consider post-processing to
   filter NPs shorter than 2 characters or containing only punctuation.

6. The exercise asks for a networkx graph visualization of entity co-occurrence, but the
   script only produces the trajectory scatter plot. Consider adding a network graph for
   the Diving Deeper bonus points.

7. Token counts for both episodes (7378 and 7237) seem plausible for first-100-sentences
   subsets, but the script computes density using full-text token counts while only
   extracting entities from the first 100 sentences. This makes the density calculation
   inaccurate -- it should either tokenize only the same 100 sentences, or process all
   sentences. Currently the density is underestimated.
